results.notes:
Growing gregariously, somewhat clustered, under Cedar and oak trees. Rooted in soil, amongst the grass.

Caps are 1.5 cm – 4 cm wide and are dry to the touch. Smooth or a little hair and umbonate shaped, when young. As they mature they become almost striate due to their wavy or umbilicated shape. Both young and old are light brown with pink or orange hues. Lightens considerably when dried.

Gills are radially arranged, widely spaced, rounded-edged ridges and are attached to stipe. Cinnamon coloured, like the rest of the cap and body. There is no annulus or veil present. Spore print is white.

Stem is rooting type, velutinous to bald, with a bit of grooved indentations running down it. Measuring 0.5 cm-1.5 cm. thickness and 2 cm – 4.5 cm in length.

results.notes: They were found under a half-burnt fallen pine or may be oak (the tree was moved), on wet soft sandy soil with some small roots. From distance, they look like peat mold (Chromelosporium). Largest size is around 1 cm. Several small mushrooms were found on surface, and larger puffballs were found in a small soil cavity. They are covered by yellow wool. They have darker brain-like structure inside and a reddish umbilical cord at the bottom. They are very delicate and are damaged by touching. They cannot be cut by knife because they are too soft, like cottage cheese. Samples were dried.
